# Advanced Selectors

## Children

### `e1 e2` | Descendant

Selects **ALL** `e2` elements under `e1`

### `e1 > e2` | Direct Descendant

Selects `e2` elements immediately under `e1`

- Only one (1) level below

## Siblings

### `e1 ~ e2` | General Sibling

Selects **all** `e2` elements...

- On the same level as `e1`
- After `e1`

### `e1 + e2` | Adjacent Sibling

Selects **one** `e2` element...

- On the same level as `e1`
- **Immediately after** `e1`

## Pseudo-selectors

|               | Pseudo-class | Pseudo-element |
| :-----------: | :----------: | :------------: |
|    Prefix     |     `:`      |      `::`      |
| DOM Existence |     Yes      |       No       |

## Pseudo-classes

### Dynamic / User Action

#### Selection

##### `:focus`

- Applied when element is currently **selected**
- Either via cursor or keyboard

##### `:hover`

- Applied when element is under the cursor / mouse
- Commonly used on buttons, links, drop-down menus

##### `:active`

- Applied when element is currently **being selected**
- e.g. user is clicking on it

#### Links

- Can be applied to elements with the `href` attribute
- Similar to `[href]` attribute selector

##### `:link`

- Applied to **unvisited** links

##### `:visited`

- Applied to **visited** links

### Structural

#### `:root`

- Represents top-most element
- Element with no parent
- Mostly similar with `html` selector, but has few differences

> Global CSS rules are often applied to the `:root` class
>
> - Custom common properties
> - Variables
> - `box-sizing: border-box`

#### As children

The following pseudo-classes are applied on the **element itself** that is desired to be selected, not their parent.

For example,

```css
div:first-child {
  /* ... */
}
```

- Would select `<div>`'s that are the first child of any element
- **NOT** the first child of `<div>` elements

##### `:first-child`

Select elements that are the first child of their parents

##### `:last-child`

Select elements that are the last child of their parents

##### `:only-child`

Select elements that are the only child of their parents

##### `:nth-child(n)`

Select elements that are the `n`-th child of their parents

- Acts like a function
- Argument `n` can have different forms
  - `:nth-child(2)` selects the 2nd children
  - `:nth-child(2n)` selects every 2nd child
  - `:nth-child(n + 3)` selects every children after the 3rd child
  - `:nth-child(2n + 3)` selects every 2nd children after the 3rd child
  - `:nth-child(even)` selects every even-numbered child
  - `:nth-child(odd)` selects every odd-numbered child
  - `:nth-child(-n + 3)` selects every children within the first 3 children
    - i.e. selects the first 3 children
    - The inverse of `:nth-child(n + 3)`
    - Selects all children except those after the 3rd
  - `:nth-child(-2n + 3)` selects every 2nd child within the first 3 children

#### As parents

- Applied / Selects elements as parents
- Based on their children

##### `:empty`

Selects elements that have no children

## Pseudo-elements

### `::marker`

Applied to the list markers, i.e.

- The numbers in an `<ol>`
- The bullets in an `<ul>`

### Content

#### `::first-letter`

Applied to the first letter of an element's content

#### `::first-line`

Applied to the first line of an element's content

#### `::selection`

Applied to the element's content when it is highlighted

### Content affixes

The content added by the following...

- appear to be non-selectable
- can be styled within the pseudo-element selector
- can be any of the following:
  - string (more text content)
  - image (either actual image file or gradient)
  - counter
    - Think list markers
    - They may be added this way...
  - nothing (add pure styling)

#### `::before`

- Content **preceding** the element's content
- Think **prefix**

#### `::after`

- Content **following** the element's content
- Think **suffix**

## Attributes

### `[attr]` | Existence

Selects elements that has the specified `attr`

- Does not care for the actual value of the attribute

### `elem[attr]` | Particular element

Selects `elem` elements that has the specified `attr`

- Element selection can be any of the regular selectors
- Attribute selection can be any of the following

### `[attr="value"]` | Exact

Selects elements whose `attr` value is exactly the specified `"value"`

### `[attr^="pre"]` | Starts with...

Selects elements whose `attr` value starts with the specified `"pre"`

- In regex, `^` denotes the start of a line

### `[attr$="post"]` | Ends with...

Selects elements whose `attr` value ends with the specified `"post"`

- In regex, `$` denotes the end of a line

### `[attr*="in"]` | Contains...

Selects elements whose `attr` value contains the specified `"in"` anywhere

- In regex, `*` denotes _zero or more of [a preceding token]_
- Think glob
- Wildcard

## Knowledge Check

- What is the difference between the child combinator and the descendant combinator?

  - In this context, "child" would refer to the "direct descendant" of an element
  - The _child combinator_ will select elements that are **directly below** a preceding element
  - The _descendant combinator_ will select **ALL** elements below a preceding element

- How does the syntax of pseudo-classes and pseudo-elements differ?

  - Pseudo-classes start with a single colon `:`
  - Pseudo-elements start with double colons `::`

- Do pseudo-classes exist somewhere in HTML? Do pseudo-elements?

  - The elements on which _pseudo-classes_ are applied **actually exists** in the source HTML
  - The elements on which _pseudo-elements_ are applied (and create) **do NOT exist** in the source HTML

- Name two ways you could select every second child of an element, starting with the first.

  - `:nth-child(2n + 1)`
    - `:nth-child(2n)` would select every 2nd child
    - Also effectively even-ordered child
    - Offsetting by `+ 1` would start counting at the 1st child
    - Put another way, `+ 1` would start on the 1st child, then `2n` would select every 2nd child after that
  - `:nth-child(odd)`
    - `2n` is effectively `even`
    - Offsetting it by 1 would produce `odd`

- What is the difference between `div:first-child` and `div:last-child`? What will each select?

  - Their difference is that they select one of the ends of an extreme
  - `div:first-child` would select `<div>`'s that are the first child of whatever element
  - `div:last-child` would select `<div>`'s that are the last child of whatever element

- What selector would you use to style a button a user is currently hovering over? How about one that is currently being clicked on?

  - `button:hover`
  - `button:active`

- How could you select all input elements with a type of text?

  - `input[type="text"]`

- How could you select all classes that begin with thunder?

  - `[class^="thunder"]`
